{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 386 "When the Digits value \+
was changed, the values of ans_exact and ans_approx were not changed. \+
 If they were not changed, then why are the values diff_10 and diff_10
0 different?  What is Maple doing different when Digits = 10 as compar
ed to Digits = 100, so that diff_10 and diff_100 are different?  (The \+
point of this question is to verbally clarify what floating point arit
hmetic means.)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 488 "With Digits=10, Maple is only keeping track of the first
 10 digits, while with digits=100, Maple is keeping track of the first
 100 digits.  With digits=10, the first 10 digits of ans_approx and an
s_exact were the same, so to Maple the difference was zero.  With digi
ts=100, and without calculating new values with digits=100, Maple calc
ulated the difference to the number of digits present in the original \+
values, which was less than 100 digits, but gave an answer much greate
r than zero." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
284 2 "kp" }{TEXT -1 6 "  Okay" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
